1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:24,655
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassam

2
00:00:25,984 --> 00:00:34,456
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,835 --> 00:00:55,823
So for those of you who listened to my earlier talks, I'm following the life of the Buddha and we got as far as his enlightenment and then we went into details about Mara, the evil one, and I had only meant to

4
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:13,444
take one talk over the hindrances, but I ended up taking two, and I haven't finished them yet, so I don't want to overplay that, so I'm going to leave the other ones, aversion, doubt and all that, which I'm sure you know anyway.

5
00:01:15,308 --> 00:01:20,436
So I wanted to move on to the question of, so what was his awakening?

6
00:01:20,956 --> 00:01:23,379
What was it that he discovered?

7
00:01:23,561 --> 00:01:53,096
and how did that translate into practice and I'm not going to say anything which is going to surprise you but at least it's just an occasion to reflect on what his awakening was all about so if we go back to that point where he's sitting by the roadside and the rice pudding turns up and this enlivens him and fills him with great glee as you know rice pudding does

8
00:01:53,903 --> 00:02:15,793
and he went off to make the great determination to sit beneath the tree saying that he would not rise from this posture even if he were to die and so he sat there and he went to sit remember with that memory of the child the child who was watching his father doing the ploughing ceremony

9
00:02:16,550 --> 00:02:31,251
ability of the child just to receive especially you know around about the age of one onwards you know to about six just that ability to let the jaw drop and the eyes wide open

10
00:02:31,602 --> 00:02:35,407
And just that entire receptivity with no mentation at all.

11
00:02:35,729 --> 00:02:45,484
There's nothing guarding anything coming in because there's not enough history, there's not enough experience to block or to play around with.

12
00:02:45,743 --> 00:02:52,395
So seeing his father doing the ploughing ceremony was a surprise, it was a joy for him.

13
00:02:53,623 --> 00:03:08,421
And with that, what we now understand to be sati, that awareness, sati paññā, with intuitive intelligence, just that receptiveness, which is the definition of equanimity, remember, the ability to receive without reaction.

14
00:03:08,442 --> 00:03:16,312
He went and sat, and luckily for him, and for us of course, he finally cracked the puzzle.

15
00:03:16,632 --> 00:03:18,294
He's koan.

16
00:03:18,313 --> 00:03:20,597
Is there an end to suffering?

17
00:03:21,157 --> 00:03:21,217
And

18
00:03:21,923 --> 00:03:36,020
The context of his awakening, it's the normal one that's, shall we say, accepted was his insight into past lives, his own past lives.

19
00:03:36,882 --> 00:03:47,155
His insight or his being able to see how people were reborn according to their moral or immoral actions.

20
00:03:47,590 --> 00:03:52,262
And that he knew that the Asawa were completely destroyed.

21
00:03:52,322 --> 00:03:57,234
The floods will come back to them.

22
00:03:57,253 --> 00:04:00,401
So there are these three things that he understood.

23
00:04:01,580 --> 00:04:13,234
The first one, when he was able to review his past lives and understand how he got to where he was then, it became a personal understanding, you might say a personal law.

24
00:04:13,974 --> 00:04:24,026
But when that ability to go beyond himself, to see other beings arising and passing away according to what became the law of karma,

25
00:04:24,007 --> 00:04:28,050
What had been a personal law then becomes a cosmic law.

26
00:04:28,310 --> 00:04:29,192
And that's what he taught.

27
00:04:29,232 --> 00:04:31,954
He taught the law of karma and the law of rebirth.

28
00:04:34,016 --> 00:04:40,802
And the Asawa, these floods, as they're called, there are three of them.

29
00:04:41,783 --> 00:04:46,788
Normally there are three, then somebody added a fourth one in the later scriptures.

30
00:04:46,947 --> 00:04:51,853
The first one is, of course, the flood of Asawa.

31
00:04:52,610 --> 00:05:22,262
desire for sensual pleasure here sensual you have to stretch out a bit to include emotional you know emotional pleasure it's the pleasure of the senses which includes the mind and heart so it's the whole pleasure syndrome seeking pleasure in the phenomenal world or in the transient world and the second one is of course the desire to become to continue to keep reappearing as myself

32
00:05:23,120 --> 00:05:24,802
And the third one is ignorance.

33
00:05:25,302 --> 00:05:31,269
And the ignorance was then reinforced by the idea of this flood of wrong view.

34
00:05:31,608 --> 00:05:37,536
So in a sense the wrong view is an expression of ignorance as to why they added on, I don't know.

35
00:05:37,555 --> 00:05:43,382
But those three were the basic asava that he had destroyed.

36
00:05:43,983 --> 00:05:52,451
These asava, these floods, it's like the image that I have is of a painting.

37
00:05:52,516 --> 00:05:58,103
of a watercolour, where the artist first puts a wash across the back.

38
00:05:58,144 --> 00:06:02,009
Sometimes you get watercolours on a black background, don't you?

39
00:06:02,028 --> 00:06:04,333
Or at least I've seen them like that.

40
00:06:04,353 --> 00:06:05,754
They might use oil, I can't remember.

41
00:06:05,975 --> 00:06:08,718
But anyway, they put a wash on the back, you see.

42
00:06:08,999 --> 00:06:11,702
And this wash gives the whole picture a certain tone.

43
00:06:12,985 --> 00:06:19,012
So if we look at our mind-heart complex, the psyche...

44
00:06:19,668 --> 00:06:22,593
then it has these three basic tones.

45
00:06:22,694 --> 00:06:40,629
It has the tone of seeking happiness in sensual pleasure, the tone of wanting to become, to become, to become, and the tone of that ignorance, which is that wrong relationship that we have with the world we're in.

46
00:06:42,516 --> 00:06:48,324
Now, when he talks about the world we're in, he then talks about the Four Noble Truths.

47
00:06:49,206 --> 00:07:03,726
And these Four Noble Truths, the truth of, you know, that there is suffering, just a straightforward statement, the cause of suffering, which is that desire for sensual pleasure in the phenomenal world, and that there is an end, so there's your prognosis, not bad, is it?

48
00:07:04,408 --> 00:07:10,435
That there is an end to this constant misery, and that there's a path which leads to that place.

49
00:07:11,517 --> 00:07:12,439
And

50
00:07:13,026 --> 00:07:35,220
in the Four Noble Truths you'll get one way he says it where he says loke in this world there is suffering when he then defines loke he says in this fathom length body so

51
00:07:35,605 --> 00:07:45,512
this suffering, this karma, this onward going, this samsara, is happening actually within us, within the mind itself.

52
00:07:48,235 --> 00:07:54,821
And what he discovered was that there was a position which lay beyond that.

53
00:07:55,541 --> 00:07:56,923
A position which lay beyond that.

54
00:07:57,363 --> 00:08:00,425
And I've got a couple of quotes, if I can find them here.

55
00:08:02,608 --> 00:08:04,870
So, one of them is, for instance...

56
00:08:06,165 --> 00:08:07,267
There is a sphere.

57
00:08:07,307 --> 00:08:20,350
Now, a sphere, an āyātana, is a level of experience which don't overlap.

58
00:08:20,569 --> 00:08:21,812
So, for instance,

59
00:08:21,791 --> 00:08:25,478
Through our eyes we see form and colour.

60
00:08:25,619 --> 00:08:28,723
Through our nose we have this smell or aroma.

61
00:08:29,365 --> 00:08:34,453
And you can't see through your nose and you can't smell through your eyes.

62
00:08:34,754 --> 00:08:36,697
I mean, you can try, but it doesn't happen.

63
00:08:37,720 --> 00:08:39,623
And that's what he means by a sphere.

64
00:08:39,923 --> 00:08:43,529
So there are six spheres, the sixth one being the mind itself.

65
00:08:44,860 --> 00:08:58,375
And now he's saying that there is another sphere, there is a sphere, which is to be experienced, direct experience, where the eye stops and perception, and the perception of form fades away, or disappears.

66
00:08:59,096 --> 00:09:01,399
And that perception is the mental noting.

67
00:09:02,120 --> 00:09:08,606
So there's a sphere where form and perception disappears, to do with the eye.

68
00:09:08,927 --> 00:09:11,551
The same with ear and sound, they disappear.

69
00:09:11,591 --> 00:09:13,753
The perception of sound disappears.

70
00:09:14,087 --> 00:09:28,150
like that's a bird or that's pleasant, the nose and smells, aroma, the tongue and its tastes, body with its sensation, and the intellect with its mental objects, so the images and the thoughts.

71
00:09:28,171 --> 00:09:29,594
All that disappear.

72
00:09:30,375 --> 00:09:32,839
And he says this fear should be realized.

73
00:09:32,903 --> 00:09:50,153
So there he is pointing to something which goes beyond this body, this mind, this heart, the five khandhas, the five aggregates, and as he uses them here, the six spheres or the six avenues of consciousness.

74
00:09:51,398 --> 00:09:54,703
So we can only know the world through these six consciousnesses.

75
00:09:55,245 --> 00:10:00,434
We can only see it, smell it, hear it and so on and we can only know it as an internal image.

76
00:10:01,998 --> 00:10:04,783
So what he's saying is that there's a place beyond that.

77
00:10:05,640 --> 00:10:12,330
Having stated that, he points out that this can't be got by a simple act of will.

78
00:10:12,510 --> 00:10:17,597
You just can't get there by saying, well, okay, let's take a rocket or something and get up to that sphere.

79
00:10:17,758 --> 00:10:19,299
It just doesn't happen like that.

80
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:20,442
It's beyond the will.

81
00:10:20,501 --> 00:10:21,823
It's beyond the self.

82
00:10:22,845 --> 00:10:34,922
And if you remember his next talk, having laid out, at least this is in the mythology, the way the scriptures were later collected, he then talked about the self.

83
00:10:36,488 --> 00:11:00,149
now this sphere that is to be known which is beyond all else is beyond the dualistic world, it's beyond objects and therefore it can't be known as an object so it's something which is totally subjective experience

84
00:11:00,417 --> 00:11:10,207
and it cannot be known as an object, and therefore, somehow, we have to, as it were, approach it by some little trick.

85
00:11:10,626 --> 00:11:22,469
So, what all the Buddha is saying is, all you have to do is look at whatever is arising and passing away and simply know that that's not me, not mine.

86
00:11:22,489 --> 00:11:27,317
So here, the knowledge comes into a direct practice.

87
00:11:27,337 --> 00:11:31,926
And that's what he means by this satipanya, this awareness and intelligence.

88
00:11:32,664 --> 00:11:48,249
And he's saying that if we can take this position within ourselves of the observer, if we can find that observation post and begin to see things within ourselves as objects, then very slowly at least we'll be very clear as to what we are not.

89
00:11:49,010 --> 00:11:55,841
And it's presumed that if we're very clear as to what we're not, then hopefully, eventually, we'll be very clear as to what we actually are.

90
00:11:57,524 --> 00:12:00,207
That's the idea, anyway, of the practice.

91
00:12:01,554 --> 00:12:02,960
So,

92
00:12:09,789 --> 00:12:10,811
How do we do that?

93
00:12:12,394 --> 00:12:16,418
What process do we use in order to access that vantage point?

94
00:12:16,458 --> 00:12:19,803
We can begin to investigate things so that it liberates.

95
00:12:20,664 --> 00:12:21,647
What's it liberating?

96
00:12:21,746 --> 00:12:25,351
It's liberating that which is this special sphere.

97
00:12:26,472 --> 00:12:33,503
And what is the content or what is that made up of?

98
00:12:33,482 --> 00:12:41,839
It's the sati, it's the paññā, it's the awareness and the wisdom, it's the looking, it's the seeing, it's the looking and the seeing.

99
00:12:42,460 --> 00:12:46,548
So he always says, first of all, you look and then you see.

100
00:12:46,988 --> 00:12:52,018
So if you take that into your life, in ordinary day life, you can see that first of all, you've got to look.

101
00:12:52,438 --> 00:12:55,465
If something goes wrong with the car, you've got to open the bonnet and have a look.

102
00:12:55,485 --> 00:12:56,807
And then when you look, you see.

103
00:12:58,171 --> 00:13:06,407
So it's the same with anything, that process of looking, but we're looking, remember, with that attitude of wanting to know.

104
00:13:06,427 --> 00:13:07,850
So that has to be there.

105
00:13:07,889 --> 00:13:12,298
There has to be that desire of wanting to know.

106
00:13:13,325 --> 00:13:15,609
what is it that we want to know?

107
00:13:15,928 --> 00:13:21,798
We cannot know Nirvana, we cannot know the end of suffering directly, we cannot turn round upon it and say, gotcha.

108
00:13:22,339 --> 00:13:23,320
See, it doesn't work like that.

109
00:13:24,302 --> 00:13:37,442
So, if you think of an archer, this is an image that works for me anyway, when they are firing the arrow at the distant target, they never point it at the target directly, they're always pointing it up in the air somewhere.

110
00:13:38,080 --> 00:13:44,072
And they know that if it travels at a certain speed and it passes through that point, it's going to hit the target.

111
00:13:45,655 --> 00:13:50,986
So the Buddha shifts that sort of investigation away from Nibbana.

112
00:13:51,006 --> 00:13:51,828
He says, don't worry about that.

113
00:13:51,948 --> 00:13:53,974
He says, that will arise in its own good time.

114
00:13:54,514 --> 00:13:58,923
He says, just shift it towards the way you are looking.

115
00:13:59,207 --> 00:14:18,144
So this element that we have in us, in Theravada, it's dryly referred to as the Nibbana Datu, the element of Nibbana, which I think takes on a certain fleshy quality when you call it Bodhicitta, the heart-seeking enlightenment.

116
00:14:18,686 --> 00:14:21,991
So when that...

117
00:14:22,731 --> 00:14:44,182
arises when when when we actually bring that forward by lifting this awareness to look at what is happening within the body and mind he says don't worry about nibbana he says just see how you're looking and then he gives us these three vantage points the anicca the dukkha the anatta

118
00:14:44,163 --> 00:14:45,664
the sense of impermanence.

119
00:14:47,087 --> 00:14:48,890
Where is the suffering?

120
00:14:49,191 --> 00:14:49,851
Where is it?

121
00:14:50,011 --> 00:14:53,457
Where is it in this complex of the body, mind, heart?

122
00:14:53,918 --> 00:14:55,000
Where is the suffering?

123
00:14:55,039 --> 00:14:56,302
Where is it arising from?

124
00:14:56,923 --> 00:14:58,966
What's actually the cause of that suffering?

125
00:14:59,947 --> 00:15:04,095
And then the more subtle teaching of not-self.

126
00:15:05,458 --> 00:15:20,097
So, he's taken our gaze away from worrying about nibbana, worrying about liberation, lots of stuff, and he says, why not investigate what you are experiencing from these three vantage points?

127
00:15:20,118 --> 00:15:32,293
So, when we're looking, and we take the vantage point of anicca, of transience and impermanence, we're becoming aware of that quality that everything is in a process of change.

128
00:15:32,442 --> 00:15:41,394
Now, if we center simply on that, you see, then you'll find that the mind is very much aware of the beginning of things, but not the end of things.

129
00:15:42,235 --> 00:15:47,381
Because beginning, new for us, symbolizes something exciting.

130
00:15:48,383 --> 00:15:54,230
Even if it's something horrible, there's still a sense of awareness that it is beginning.

131
00:15:55,392 --> 00:16:01,179
then as it begins to end, our attention really goes to what is the next beginning.

132
00:16:01,541 --> 00:16:07,107
So we always know who the new film star is or pop star, but we never actually know what happens to them.

133
00:16:08,090 --> 00:16:08,850
They've disappeared.

134
00:16:08,890 --> 00:16:16,500
They just fade away from consciousness, from cultural consciousness.

135
00:16:17,302 --> 00:16:24,893
So by putting the attention on the ending of things, on the ending of things, we begin to see that actually

136
00:16:25,327 --> 00:16:28,792
This process, this process of change is not a continuum.

137
00:16:30,114 --> 00:16:31,395
There is an actual stopping.

138
00:16:31,716 --> 00:16:32,817
There is an actual stopping.

139
00:16:34,679 --> 00:16:43,291
The image there is of a row of billiard balls.

140
00:16:44,932 --> 00:16:48,197
So they're all joined up together but they're actually all separate.

141
00:16:49,155 --> 00:17:04,218
Usually that's explained as showing the difference between the Buddhist position on this and the Hindu position which says that there's something which continues through the arising and passing away of things.

142
00:17:04,739 --> 00:17:06,922
So it's like a row of beads with a string through it.

143
00:17:08,845 --> 00:17:11,608
But the Buddhist position is radical change.

144
00:17:11,829 --> 00:17:16,175
It's actually something completely finishes before something else can begin.

145
00:17:16,644 --> 00:17:32,375
And that radical change, as we get into it, you see, so as we get into it, there's a seeing of it from the point of view of the intellect, the point of view of actually understanding things arise and pass away.

146
00:17:34,127 --> 00:17:39,396
but it's actually at the emotional level, it's at the heart level that it begins to strike home.

147
00:17:39,938 --> 00:17:55,545
So even though in our school we go for the minuscule, we go for the actual seeing of things in the minute, watching the rising and falling of the breath and even eventually the rising and falling of a sequence of sensations,

148
00:17:55,525 --> 00:17:59,148
At the heart level, it doesn't have to be that particular find at all.

149
00:17:59,729 --> 00:18:06,715
Somebody close to us who dies can hit you just as hard as watching the arising and falling of the breath.

150
00:18:07,537 --> 00:18:09,439
And it's hitting at a point of attitude.

151
00:18:10,339 --> 00:18:15,644
And when that attitude is broken, this has some continuity.

152
00:18:15,786 --> 00:18:20,250
When that attitude is broken, it reverberates back onto our understanding.

153
00:18:20,230 --> 00:18:50,000
so there's always different ways in which the quality of transience can strike us and it's constantly putting that attention there that there is this slow beginning to understand what's happening now what is it that's arising and passing away so remember that the Buddha's teaching is that everything is mind our knowledge of the outside world is totally dependent upon the senses that we have

154
00:18:50,301 --> 00:19:09,838
So even though we're in this room together and nobody would dispute that this meditation hall actually sort of exists when we go away, in other words our mind is not actually creating this hall, the fact of the matter is all of us have walked into it, we all have a different view of it, a slightly different feel of it and so on.

155
00:19:10,439 --> 00:19:20,307
So in a sense our experience of this hall is all varied, individual and that's true for everything we experience.

156
00:19:20,288 --> 00:19:47,847
it's only through language and general communication that we can get across to people that we generally see the world as they do and of course some we don't and therefore you get this image of parallel universes we're all sort of running parallel to each other in some way sometimes we sort of crash a bit but the idea is that everything that I know is within my mind

157
00:19:47,827 --> 00:20:10,157
So all these stimuli, the light, the smells, the touch and all that, they're all being brought into this central box which we call the brain, but there's also, in Buddhist understanding, a mind matter there, which is a more subtle form, which produces for us a picture.

158
00:20:10,999 --> 00:20:15,625
Now we know that from our own knowledge of how the brain works.

159
00:20:15,605 --> 00:20:21,082
This picture that we get is, shall we say, that act of cognition.

160
00:20:22,065 --> 00:20:23,509
And there's something that knows it.

161
00:20:23,609 --> 00:20:26,598
There's something that knows, that has a double take on it.

162
00:20:26,618 --> 00:20:27,582
It knows it knows.

163
00:20:28,183 --> 00:20:28,263
Hmm?

164
00:20:29,392 --> 00:20:47,990
and that picture as it were is arising and passing away holding an image for us so that we can grasp it and then it disappears and the next image comes up dependent on the stimuli coming in from the outside through the senses or from the inside through our memories

165
00:20:48,477 --> 00:20:59,378
And when we see that the world is arising and passing away, I think personally it would be truer to say that what we're watching is our minds arising and passing away.

166
00:20:59,398 --> 00:21:01,865
The actual act of cognition.

167
00:21:01,884 --> 00:21:08,898
Now to see that is of course undermines the idea that I can be that.

168
00:21:09,384 --> 00:21:26,701
so anicca the quality of transience does refer back to the self and this is what the Buddha said if you remember in the discourse that I read is something which arises and passes away to be understood as me, mine and so on

169
00:21:26,682 --> 00:21:35,499
So that quality of radical impermanence does reflect back to the not-self.

170
00:21:35,519 --> 00:21:44,336
And in so doing, of course, it ruptures a type of relationship that we have, which is a holding on.

171
00:21:45,463 --> 00:21:56,615
Remember that the self is constantly trying to build a world of comfort around itself, a sort of castle, so that it doesn't shake, it doesn't fear anything, it doesn't fear death.

172
00:21:57,497 --> 00:22:10,289
But to see that anicca quality, that real radical arising and passing away, reverberates back onto the self in its relationship to the world it's in.

173
00:22:10,269 --> 00:22:13,035
Now, there I said the relationship of the self.

174
00:22:13,055 --> 00:22:13,535
That was wrong.

175
00:22:13,596 --> 00:22:20,467
It's a relationship of this satipanya, of this bodhicitta or this nirvana dhātu.

176
00:22:20,567 --> 00:22:27,719
It depends what school you're in and what you feel happy with, what expression you feel happy with.

177
00:22:28,881 --> 00:22:29,982
So now...

178
00:22:30,554 --> 00:22:50,976
we're getting this idea that there is something within us, this awareness, this very basic intuitive intelligence which is at the root of our being, and it moves into every moment with some sort of wrong view, some sort of wrong view, and that not knowing

179
00:22:50,955 --> 00:23:01,002
It comes from the position of not knowing is the basis of, the beginning of, the wheel of dependence origination, which is how the Buddha explains how we come to suffer.

180
00:23:02,185 --> 00:23:07,480
Now, I think I said before in an earlier talk, when I was answering a question,

181
00:23:08,624 --> 00:23:16,417
If we go back to our little origins in this particular life, remember that we became alive as just a bundle of cells.

182
00:23:16,798 --> 00:23:18,922
So in that bundle, what did we know?

183
00:23:18,942 --> 00:23:24,432
And it's only through the growth of the senses that we come to collect, as it were, enough information.

184
00:23:24,873 --> 00:23:29,340
And then finally we find ourselves out in the open world and gasping for a bit of breath.

185
00:23:29,861 --> 00:23:30,982
And then we grow up.

186
00:23:31,023 --> 00:23:33,567
And all the time...

187
00:23:33,548 --> 00:23:41,325
there's this presumption, which is gained right back there in the womb, that this must be me, because this is what I experience.

188
00:23:41,345 --> 00:23:53,750
Now, that delusion stays with us all the time, and it's only through meditation, by taking this objective position in ourselves, that we begin to break through that delusion.

189
00:23:54,102 --> 00:24:04,952
And the process of an nature of transience, of impermanence, is coming from a slightly different angle, which is saying that even if you hold on to it, it's going to disappear.

190
00:24:05,693 --> 00:24:06,674
Nothing stays the same.

191
00:24:06,755 --> 00:24:08,897
Everything is in a state of radical change.

192
00:24:08,978 --> 00:24:16,005
So that even the effort to try and hold on to something, to maintain a comfort, is a non-starter.

193
00:24:16,404 --> 00:24:17,967
It's not going to get you anywhere.

194
00:24:19,364 --> 00:24:25,333
So watching Anicca, even at the breath, is a constant undermining of that wrong view.

195
00:24:26,694 --> 00:24:31,201
A wrong view, remember, that has not come from a position of stupidity.

196
00:24:31,402 --> 00:24:34,747
That's the unfortunate thing about this English word ignorance.

197
00:24:35,268 --> 00:24:38,992
There is another word, nescience, but nobody knows it, so there's no point in it.

198
00:24:40,188 --> 00:24:43,957
Only the dictionary knows that word.

199
00:24:44,136 --> 00:24:46,082
And it means a simple don't know.

200
00:24:46,122 --> 00:24:47,746
Don't know, you see.

201
00:24:48,247 --> 00:24:50,471
And from that don't know is a frightening place to be.

202
00:24:51,153 --> 00:24:56,526
So one throws oneself into something, defines oneself as something.

203
00:24:56,506 --> 00:25:08,439
Now this has happened to you all, I'm sure, at a time when you've, say, been in a strange hotel or in somebody's house and you've just woken up and you don't know where you are.

204
00:25:09,519 --> 00:25:13,365
And there's that sudden sort of rush of panic as to who you are.

205
00:25:14,346 --> 00:25:19,030
And it's only when you remember that, oh, you're in this hotel, that you can breathe again.

206
00:25:19,852 --> 00:25:22,615
Now that panic, you see, is the self.

207
00:25:22,595 --> 00:25:25,681
At that moment, the self can't define itself.

208
00:25:25,701 --> 00:25:29,087
So it's rushing around like a mad fool, trying to work out what the hell it is.

209
00:25:30,250 --> 00:25:35,000
And so when it grasps it, fantastic, then it's happy.

210
00:25:35,079 --> 00:25:36,182
Oh, it's me again.

211
00:25:39,030 --> 00:25:58,490
So that sense of transience, really seeing transience, is not only coming back to the idea that nothing in this world is worth holding on to, that's a direct quote from the Buddha, but the fact that if it's transient it can't be me, because it's arising and passing away.

212
00:25:58,471 --> 00:26:13,527
So as we're watching it at all levels, remember at all levels, whether it's right there in the minuscule arising and passing away of a sensation, or whether we're just watching these leaves fall, and just watching the change of leaves, and just catching our feeling towards it.

213
00:26:13,507 --> 00:26:22,932
Sometimes if you stand by a river, just watch the river coming at you and just catch your feelings that come up with that coming, the newness.

214
00:26:23,375 --> 00:26:28,950
And then turn around and watch it flowing away and just catch how your feelings are at letting something go.

215
00:26:30,195 --> 00:26:37,430
If there's a puddle around or a pond, look into that and see how you feel when there is no flow.

216
00:26:39,113 --> 00:26:45,365
So it's not as though we have to do this meditation in order to break through these things.

217
00:26:45,625 --> 00:26:52,980
All this meditation is doing for us is making more and more clear to us what this satipaññā is.

218
00:26:52,960 --> 00:27:19,643
so if we sit with the idea that right now I'm going to crack it I'm going to really break through this sitting like the Buddha did you can try it it usually ends up with severe frustration so if we see our sitting simply as training all we're doing is we're just training ourselves to constantly lift ourselves into this position of at least the objective observer

219
00:27:22,103 --> 00:27:28,073
Now, from this position of not-self, we've created these delusions.

220
00:27:28,413 --> 00:27:31,799
The fundamental delusion is that I am this person.

221
00:27:32,299 --> 00:27:33,382
That's the fundamental delusion.

222
00:27:33,442 --> 00:27:35,405
I am this personality and I am this body.

223
00:27:36,067 --> 00:27:38,912
And those we call our sankaras.

224
00:27:39,573 --> 00:27:45,563
And a sankara is all those things that we've been able to create through an act of will.

225
00:27:45,542 --> 00:27:50,307
So once you've got a body and you've got an eye, the eye will see, that's not a Sankara.

226
00:27:50,327 --> 00:27:53,090
Whatever's coming into the eye is a given.

227
00:27:53,111 --> 00:28:04,303
What we do with that which comes into the eye, or with the image that comes, that's our Sankaras, because there comes that intention into what we're doing.

228
00:28:04,682 --> 00:28:12,411
And that's building up a mood, it's building up an attitude, and it's building up a whole series of thoughts, it's building up a history.

229
00:28:12,391 --> 00:28:32,121
these intentions remember at all levels in all areas of our lives turn into an action so you have an intention it turns into an action when you've got similar actions going on you've produced a habit and once you've got a compendium of these habits a collection of habits that's your personality

230
00:28:32,641 --> 00:28:37,887
And once you've got a personality, it just drives you towards your destiny, until, of course, you come to meditate.

231
00:28:38,548 --> 00:28:43,556
And then you can reverse some of it, and hopefully end up with a decent destiny.

232
00:28:46,140 --> 00:28:55,132
So, here we are, with this satipanya, this awareness, this buddho within ourselves, and then we're born.

233
00:28:55,613 --> 00:28:58,817
So that's the next stage, nama-rupa, you're born.

234
00:28:59,067 --> 00:29:05,818
And with that being born, there arises these acts of cognition.

235
00:29:06,420 --> 00:29:12,711
So this body-mind complex and the act of cognition rebound off each other.

236
00:29:13,113 --> 00:29:14,935
The one can't arise without the other.

237
00:29:14,996 --> 00:29:21,548
You can't cognize something if there's nothing there.

238
00:29:21,967 --> 00:29:30,201
So there can't be a cognition unless there's something coming in through the perceptual faculties, the eye and so on.

239
00:29:31,022 --> 00:29:44,606
So once that's started, once you've got that, once you've got the consciousness and the basic body, which has these six senses, so that's your next step, the salayatana, the six sense bases, then finally you can have some contact.

240
00:29:44,787 --> 00:29:46,911
And that's your next stage, your contact.

241
00:29:47,498 --> 00:29:51,568
At the point of contact, there has to be these three things.

242
00:29:51,789 --> 00:29:57,846
You have to have a sense base, you have to have something that stimulates that sense base, and you've got to have that consciousness.

243
00:29:59,394 --> 00:30:17,534
Once that arises, then the mind, the perceptual faculty comes in, which knows what it is, but then that quality of judgment, now this isn't a judgment to do with good and bad and all that, it just experiences what comes in as pleasant or unpleasant.

244
00:30:17,554 --> 00:30:19,115
It's as simple as that.

245
00:30:19,135 --> 00:30:22,720
So sometimes we get a sensation which is pleasant, unpleasant,

246
00:30:22,987 --> 00:30:28,380
like when we're eating, and sometimes we get something which is unpleasant, like when it's getting cold.

247
00:30:28,942 --> 00:30:35,436
So whatever sensation comes in, after the contact, there is this relationship built up with it.

248
00:30:35,778 --> 00:30:38,565
So the relationship is, like it, don't like it.

249
00:30:39,253 --> 00:30:47,707
Now, once the self grabs hold of that as a position, pleasant, unpleasant, you see, then it has to take a position.

250
00:30:48,488 --> 00:30:54,056
Now, its position comes from that fundamental misunderstanding that this is what it is.

251
00:30:55,097 --> 00:30:57,641
And it knows there is suffering.

252
00:30:57,661 --> 00:30:58,863
It's not happy.

253
00:31:00,425 --> 00:31:02,268
Now, what is it that's not happy?

254
00:31:03,210 --> 00:31:04,491
See, what is it that's not happy?

255
00:31:05,173 --> 00:31:08,096
So we started off way back there in the womb,

256
00:31:09,105 --> 00:31:13,071
being this, shall we say, this satipanya, this Buddha nature.

257
00:31:14,374 --> 00:31:16,017
And it's formed a relationship.

258
00:31:16,597 --> 00:31:23,828
So when we talk about the self, we're not talking about something, we're not talking about an object, we're talking about a relationship.

259
00:31:25,311 --> 00:31:26,433
We're talking about a relationship.

260
00:31:26,794 --> 00:31:32,123
So, when we're suffering, what is it that's suffering?

261
00:31:32,963 --> 00:31:34,826
If it's not this very nature,

262
00:31:35,785 --> 00:31:37,946
which is our essential nature of the Buddha.

263
00:31:38,548 --> 00:31:40,088
That's what's suffering.

264
00:31:40,108 --> 00:31:43,593
And it's suffering because it's formed this wrong relationship.

265
00:31:43,613 --> 00:31:50,740
So when we say the self, you see, there's a tendency to substantiate it.

266
00:31:50,759 --> 00:31:53,502
There's a tendency to think that it's an object.

267
00:31:54,263 --> 00:31:59,970
But we're much closer, I think, to understanding what the self is when we realize it's to do with our relationship.

268
00:32:01,367 --> 00:32:17,122
So when this perception comes, that this is pleasant and unpleasant, the knowing, which is ignorant, which is creating the delusion, says to itself, I've got to make myself happy.

269
00:32:17,382 --> 00:32:18,363
This is where happiness is.

270
00:32:18,423 --> 00:32:20,204
I've got to make it now or else I've had it.

271
00:32:20,944 --> 00:32:29,873
So whatever it sees creates a certain state, a mental state, which is happy, it'll want to grab it, hold it and develop it.

272
00:32:30,612 --> 00:32:35,037
And once it's into that relationship, that's when we get that greed in all its forms.

273
00:32:35,116 --> 00:32:37,339
It doesn't matter what it is, power, sex, drugs, rock and roll.

274
00:32:37,359 --> 00:32:38,280
It doesn't matter what it is.

275
00:32:38,820 --> 00:32:43,626
The fact is that the more I can have of it, the happier I will be.

276
00:32:43,946 --> 00:32:44,688
It's as simple as that.

277
00:32:45,709 --> 00:32:52,376
Having built that little castle, that little place of joy, now, of course, it has to protect it.

278
00:32:52,958 --> 00:33:00,365
So anything which it sees is not pleasant, then it'll want to destroy, want to annihilate, get it out, push it away.

279
00:33:00,768 --> 00:33:05,674
And whenever that is too much, when it's overwhelming, then it runs.

280
00:33:05,855 --> 00:33:06,636
It runs for it.

281
00:33:06,656 --> 00:33:08,199
It picks up its bags and goes for it.

282
00:33:08,920 --> 00:33:21,819
So there we have the fundamental psychology which arises out of that wrong perception of the self.

283
00:33:21,960 --> 00:33:22,500
This is me.

284
00:33:22,560 --> 00:33:23,122
This is mine.

285
00:33:24,002 --> 00:33:27,248
So you've got on one side the attachment...

286
00:33:27,228 --> 00:33:33,250
The holding, the developing, and on the other side, the protection and the pushing away.

287
00:33:34,375 --> 00:33:36,060
And the running away.

288
00:33:36,342 --> 00:33:38,892
That's all included in that word aversion.

289
00:33:40,423 --> 00:33:52,897
So having got to that stage, we then very quickly can move into immoral action, which is basically doing harm.

290
00:33:53,137 --> 00:33:55,701
It's doing harm to others and doing harm to myself.

291
00:33:56,781 --> 00:34:07,073
And then once I've started doing harm, I'm into the second level of emotions to do with shame, guilt, horror, all that sort of stuff, remorse, regret.

292
00:34:07,053 --> 00:34:12,478
All those flow in once I start doing something which is unwholesome.

293
00:34:12,498 --> 00:34:20,905
And of course, there are those, there's that side of the development which we take pleasure in, but which are horrible.

294
00:34:21,166 --> 00:34:24,349
So, you know, we like getting angry at people.

295
00:34:24,548 --> 00:34:25,090
It's a relief.

296
00:34:25,230 --> 00:34:26,251
We like banging the door.

297
00:34:26,951 --> 00:34:27,831
We like being cruel.

298
00:34:28,132 --> 00:34:31,936
We like, you know, stepping on people's toes and doing things like that.

299
00:34:32,635 --> 00:34:36,380
And they're just saying that little sentence which really digs them.

300
00:34:36,400 --> 00:34:36,519
And...

301
00:34:36,500 --> 00:35:03,992
and like cruelty and then not being generous being selfish you see all these things can be very pleasant so there's a whole area of unpleasant behavior which we enjoy and that of course is creating further psychological problems for us now all that all that is included in those three little steps after Vedana so the tanha

302
00:35:04,293 --> 00:35:26,418
the upadana and the bhava so the tanha is that movement from the self moving towards it because it likes it it wants it so having perceived something as likeable it now moves towards it as wantable I want that just a minute want want that ok

303
00:35:27,175 --> 00:35:35,385
Once that want has come, and this is the sequence of psychological events, according to the Buddha, the I comes in.

304
00:35:35,605 --> 00:35:36,885
See, the I doesn't come in first.

305
00:35:37,427 --> 00:35:39,248
In our language we say, I want that.

306
00:35:39,630 --> 00:35:41,331
But it's not, it's want I.

307
00:35:42,172 --> 00:35:54,347
First the desire arises, and then there's the association with the desire, there's the identification with desire, and that's the upadana, that's the grasping.

308
00:35:54,327 --> 00:36:22,679
once that's happened it's very difficult to stop the chaitanya coming in which is the will and the reason is this because that delusion of I, I want is coming, remember, directly from the Buddha the Buddha within which is deluded and with it there comes the power of the will and that's also coming from that centre

309
00:36:23,722 --> 00:36:25,606
It's also coming from that center.

310
00:36:26,208 --> 00:36:32,639
So immediately we say I, it's very difficult to stop the grasping, the actual going for the object.

311
00:36:34,123 --> 00:36:35,965
And that's the bhava, that's the becoming.

312
00:36:36,166 --> 00:36:38,530
At that point we've created an act.

313
00:36:39,432 --> 00:36:44,382
And that act now, as I say, repeated, becomes a habit.

314
00:36:47,364 --> 00:37:16,815
Now what we're trying to do in our meditation in terms of seeing the path through understanding dukkha, understanding how we create this unsatisfactory situation for ourselves is to put our attention right in between that which we perceive as likeable and unlikable and of course neutral and to catch that relationship of wanting, not wanting and ignoring.

315
00:37:16,795 --> 00:37:29,893
not wanting, just simply ignoring it simply not knowing it and if we put our attention there it can't go, it can't move anywhere else it can't go into I why is that you see?

316
00:37:30,876 --> 00:37:44,675
it's because the awareness, this intelligence we have this Buddha nature within us has taken a completely different position it's now become transcendent to the whole psychological process it's now above it or beyond it and it's watching it from above

317
00:37:45,516 --> 00:37:51,704
So, if we stay in that position, it can't go into that identity.

318
00:37:52,164 --> 00:37:53,306
It just can't do it.

319
00:37:54,047 --> 00:37:58,652
So, in that position, we're actually snapping the idea of me or mine.

320
00:37:59,494 --> 00:38:05,922
As soon as you see a desire and let it go, you're destroying constantly the idea that desire is me.

321
00:38:06,492 --> 00:38:07,552
I am the desire.

322
00:38:08,775 --> 00:38:18,688
And it's through that process of seeing that that we can find this realization through just understanding how we create suffering for ourselves.

323
00:38:18,708 --> 00:38:22,614
When I was in Thailand, I did a tour of all the different techniques.

324
00:38:23,536 --> 00:38:25,798
The Thais are very creative, you know.

325
00:38:25,818 --> 00:38:32,347
And I went down to a place called Boon Kanchan around, which is on the bay around Bangkok.

326
00:38:33,762 --> 00:38:36,666
And when I got there, the teaching, I'd heard about it.

327
00:38:37,387 --> 00:38:37,989
She had died.

328
00:38:38,309 --> 00:38:39,632
She's obviously a very good teacher.

329
00:38:40,233 --> 00:38:41,534
But the instructions are very simple.

330
00:38:42,916 --> 00:38:44,820
You don't stop doing what you're doing until it hurts.

331
00:38:45,581 --> 00:38:46,543
Really hurts.

332
00:38:46,563 --> 00:38:48,125
Really, really, really hurts.

333
00:38:48,786 --> 00:38:52,733
So you sit and it starts to hurt.

334
00:38:52,965 --> 00:38:57,050
and you're not supposed to do anything until it really, really, really hurts.

335
00:38:57,070 --> 00:39:02,835
And then, when it really, really, really hurts, and you can't handle it anymore, you then change your posture.

336
00:39:02,855 --> 00:39:11,983
But you do it very, very slowly, and all you're looking at is, as the pain arises, as the discomfort arises, you're just watching your reactions to it.

337
00:39:12,943 --> 00:39:18,688
And as it gets to the point where you can't take it anymore, and you're shaking with it, you just watch your reactions to that, you see?

338
00:39:19,289 --> 00:39:22,331
And then when it comes to a point where you really can't take it anymore...

339
00:39:24,016 --> 00:39:25,742
you say intending to change.

340
00:39:26,264 --> 00:39:34,431
And as you change, you watch very carefully how the physical body, the physical sensations are changing and how the mind is changing.

341
00:39:34,985 --> 00:39:36,927
And then you come back to a state of comfort.

342
00:39:37,447 --> 00:39:46,119
So from walking you might go to sitting, to lying down, whatever you're doing, but you keep doing it until you get to that point where you're able to see that change.

343
00:39:46,139 --> 00:39:59,659
And in seeing that change, you're seeing the distinction between pain, which is both physical and mental, and how you can take a position to it whereby you're not actually suffering.

344
00:40:01,005 --> 00:40:06,581
And by observing that process, you're actually undoing the idea of a self.

345
00:40:06,961 --> 00:40:11,193
Because the self is always identifying with that process.

346
00:40:12,376 --> 00:40:15,284
It says, oh, it's pain, I'd better go and get an aspirin.

347
00:40:15,990 --> 00:40:17,612
It's always moving off it.

348
00:40:17,672 --> 00:40:19,054
It's unable to stay with it.

349
00:40:19,916 --> 00:40:36,280
So even by going through this process of understanding dukkha, of understanding how we create suffering for ourselves, we again undermine that wrong relationship which lies at the base, which is the idea that this is me, this is mine.

350
00:40:39,364 --> 00:40:41,947
Now, when it...

351
00:40:43,260 --> 00:40:57,641
When that is finished, of course, you're also cutting the end of that process of the wheel of dependent origination, which is birth, aging, death, or arising, decay, death, arising and passing away.

352
00:40:58,599 --> 00:41:23,713
should we say the traditional teaching is three lives but the other teaching which is right there in the scriptures and is right there in the commentaries is of course moment to moment so as we see something which we like and we indulge in it then we become the indulger and that arises and passes away

353
00:41:23,693 --> 00:41:37,498
So with every sequence of actions in which we've indulged or which we've pushed away or which we've run away, we've become somebody and there was a beginning, there was a middle, there was a decaying and there was an end.

354
00:41:38,681 --> 00:41:43,170
So not everything we do is part of the wheel of independent origination.

355
00:41:43,250 --> 00:41:46,697
Not everything we do is continuing with the self.

356
00:41:46,677 --> 00:42:15,132
because for instance just some simple action like opening a door there's not a moral problem there it's only where a moral and ethical situation arises of greed, hatred or aversion that wheel can actually turn so when we do something out of a correct intention when we eat in order to nourish the body

357
00:42:15,601 --> 00:42:26,202
we eat to live, not live to eat when we eat to nourish the body then we're not turning the wheel in fact we're going backwards on the wheel

358
00:42:27,159 --> 00:42:31,264
Now, why is it that the wheel doesn't come back on itself?

359
00:42:31,583 --> 00:42:38,311
So you start off with not becoming, and then you go down to not grasping, no I, then you come back to desire.

360
00:42:38,851 --> 00:42:50,483
No, the Buddha starts the negative side of the wheel, the wheel which is drawing us to enlightenment, back at ignorance again, back at the point of this wrong view.

361
00:42:52,644 --> 00:42:55,327
And the reason he does that is because

362
00:42:55,460 --> 00:42:58,284
When we're meditating, we're always correcting that view.

363
00:42:59,065 --> 00:43:07,900
And whenever you correct a view, whenever you correct the way you're looking at something, the whole castle of cards that we've built on that wrong view simply collapses.

364
00:43:08,943 --> 00:43:10,364
You don't have to take everything apart.

365
00:43:10,786 --> 00:43:15,653
As soon as you see transience, the whole thing that you've built on transience completely collapses.

366
00:43:16,436 --> 00:43:20,202
And that's why these insights are immediate.

367
00:43:20,485 --> 00:43:24,409
Not all these insights, of course, have a colossal effect on us.

368
00:43:24,449 --> 00:43:26,811
We don't sort of jump up and down and all that sort of stuff.

369
00:43:27,492 --> 00:43:28,554
But they're little.

370
00:43:28,673 --> 00:43:32,177
They're slowly just cutting away at the delusion.

371
00:43:32,358 --> 00:43:34,641
Slowly cutting away at the delusion.

372
00:43:34,661 --> 00:43:38,224
And that's why the whole of the Buddha's teaching is concerned with right view.

373
00:43:38,806 --> 00:43:45,653
As soon as you see something, everything, you know, corrects itself.

374
00:43:45,673 --> 00:43:50,239
There was a friend of mine who was going to pick me up and we were going to go for a walk and his car broke down.

375
00:43:50,320 --> 00:43:57,096
And it was parked by the road there, so I, being an expert mechanic, said, well, open the bonnet.

376
00:43:57,757 --> 00:44:01,485
So he opened the bonnet, and he told me what had happened.

377
00:44:01,525 --> 00:44:02,387
The engine just cut.

378
00:44:03,471 --> 00:44:06,657
So my immediate diagnosis was, well, it's electrics.

379
00:44:06,824 --> 00:44:17,255
So we opened the bonnet and I pointed, you know, we tried it and I said, no, I said, it's either, it'll be the dynamo, I said.

380
00:44:17,315 --> 00:44:22,179
And I pointed at this part of the machine, I said, it'll be the dynamo.

381
00:44:22,199 --> 00:44:27,105
Anyway, the AA, I don't know what you call it in America, but the mechanic came.

382
00:44:27,125 --> 00:44:31,548
And he opened the bonnet and he immediately saw that the fan belt had broken.

383
00:44:33,217 --> 00:44:39,329
And what he pointed to as the dynamo seemed to be different from my own description of a dynamo.

384
00:44:39,869 --> 00:44:44,219
Now, if my friend had taken my advice, of course, the car would have ended up in a scrap heap.

385
00:44:44,980 --> 00:44:48,146
But luckily, somebody who knew came along and saved the day.

386
00:44:48,768 --> 00:44:54,498
So you can see how wrong view can end you up in a hole.

387
00:44:56,807 --> 00:45:19,237
so there we see you see this mechanic came along and he said and that was it as soon as that right view was there the whole problem disappeared and I felt terribly I felt a real idiot but there we are so that's why the wheel starts again with ignorance

388
00:45:19,740 --> 00:45:49,713
and that's why the whole force of the Buddha's teaching is right view to see things as they really are to understand to know and see things as they have if you want the direct translation as they have come to be to see the process it's often translated as to see things as they really are but it's not it's to see things as they have come to be

389
00:45:49,829 --> 00:45:53,492
So it's always catching that process in which we create the world we live in.

390
00:45:59,099 --> 00:46:03,182
Gee, can't stop talking.

391
00:46:03,222 --> 00:46:09,389
Then there's the final characteristic of anatta, not self.

392
00:46:09,869 --> 00:46:12,251
So we've talked about that from the point of view of anicca.

393
00:46:12,271 --> 00:46:15,195
If something arises and passes away, it can't be me, it can't be mine.

394
00:46:15,344 --> 00:46:32,322
And we talked about it through seeing this dukkha, through seeing that, in fact, if I can take this transcendent position, this transcendent position to this mental process of greed and stuff, then unwittingly I've snapped the self, I've broken the self, as soon as I'm in that position.

395
00:46:33,856 --> 00:46:44,074
There's a lovely little quote here actually to do with Anicci which I'd forgotten to read out and it's William Blake and I think he puts it in a beautiful little poetic way.

396
00:46:44,114 --> 00:46:45,556
I'm sure most of you know it.

397
00:46:46,297 --> 00:46:58,800
He who binds to himself a joy does the winged life destroy but he who kisses the joy as it flies lives in eternity's sunrise.

398
00:47:01,177 --> 00:47:05,315
So that's a lovely expression of how to, well, it's the Buddha mind.

399
00:47:05,375 --> 00:47:07,103
That's how we're supposed to be.

400
00:47:13,916 --> 00:47:33,905
Now, anatta, the doctrine of not-self, is just getting that position where, instead of within yourself, when you're watching something, you see, and you turn it into an object that you're looking at, you see, it's catching that little distance.

401
00:47:33,925 --> 00:47:39,773
Although I talk in terms of space, I mean, it just feels that you're looking at something.

402
00:47:40,106 --> 00:47:47,000
Remember that we're told that a child up to about the age of four months doesn't have that distance.

403
00:47:47,039 --> 00:47:48,061
Everything is me.

404
00:47:48,141 --> 00:47:48,943
It doesn't matter what it is.

405
00:47:49,804 --> 00:47:50,786
It's all me.

406
00:47:50,806 --> 00:47:59,262
And only slowly, after four months, does this object arise out of this bath, which is me, and his mother, isn't it?

407
00:47:59,530 --> 00:48:08,840
And that object now, as it were, becomes something in the mind of the child, something that's not me, just the beginnings of a perception.

408
00:48:09,541 --> 00:48:14,789
By the age of three, the child is very clear, this is my body and I'm not that.

409
00:48:15,349 --> 00:48:17,831
They're very clear about what their boundary is.

410
00:48:19,974 --> 00:48:22,438
All we're doing is continuing that process inward.

411
00:48:22,777 --> 00:48:24,119
That's all we're doing.

412
00:48:24,454 --> 00:48:33,409
we are slowly deciding, or rather we're slowly realizing that within us all these things that I thought were part of me is actually an object.

413
00:48:36,295 --> 00:48:41,925
And one of the things that the Buddha talks about when he talks about not-self is this idea of control.

414
00:48:41,985 --> 00:48:46,733
If the self can't control it, how can it possibly be that?

415
00:48:46,931 --> 00:48:49,135
The whole idea of being a self is that you're in control.

416
00:48:49,155 --> 00:48:49,916
This is me.

417
00:48:49,936 --> 00:48:50,516
This is mine.

418
00:48:50,856 --> 00:48:51,978
I do what I want.

419
00:48:52,018 --> 00:48:54,242
I do my own thing in my own way, in my own time.

420
00:48:55,583 --> 00:48:56,545
And of course you can't.

421
00:48:56,945 --> 00:49:04,436
So there's a constant destruction of this idea of a self every time in your ordinary daily life when you can't do what you want to do.

422
00:49:05,496 --> 00:49:07,300
If you can't do what you want to do, then you're not in control.

423
00:49:07,320 --> 00:49:09,262
Therefore you can't be the self.

424
00:49:09,282 --> 00:49:11,264
And that's the logic behind that.

425
00:49:11,806 --> 00:49:16,331
So here you see, as we go into the body, I mean even the body itself,

426
00:49:18,050 --> 00:49:19,271
I mean, we cut ourselves.

427
00:49:19,711 --> 00:49:20,231
What do we do?

428
00:49:20,271 --> 00:49:24,416
You keep it antiseptic, but who mends it?

429
00:49:24,436 --> 00:49:27,019
You're not in there telling the cells to do this and do that.

430
00:49:27,880 --> 00:49:28,981
The body just gets on with it.

431
00:49:30,744 --> 00:49:33,786
When you breathe, what do you know of your body?

432
00:49:33,827 --> 00:49:36,409
Even when you go into yourself, what do I know?

433
00:49:36,429 --> 00:49:37,610
Do you know the marrow of your bones?

434
00:49:39,152 --> 00:49:42,876
I mean, we're told we've got them, but can you perceive it?

435
00:49:42,936 --> 00:49:44,157
Can you know it's there?

436
00:49:45,927 --> 00:49:50,072
The brain, we can't even feel the brain for heaven's sake.

437
00:49:50,092 --> 00:49:52,215
At least I can't.

438
00:49:52,235 --> 00:49:54,860
Perhaps I need a cat scan.

439
00:49:54,880 --> 00:49:57,422
And then the whole system, how it's working.

440
00:49:57,724 --> 00:49:58,425
We're breathing.

441
00:50:00,027 --> 00:50:01,349
I have no control over it at all.

442
00:50:01,449 --> 00:50:04,233
If I stop breathing, I panic.

443
00:50:04,253 --> 00:50:07,177
The digestive system, I haven't a clue what goes on there.

444
00:50:07,197 --> 00:50:11,182
I mean, I'm told about enzymes and all that sort of stuff, but I don't feel anything at all.

445
00:50:11,202 --> 00:50:11,742
I just feel good.

446
00:50:11,764 --> 00:50:14,246
I haven't a clue what's happening.

447
00:50:14,766 --> 00:50:23,320
Even now, you see, if you look at me and your whole vision is filled with my face, right?

448
00:50:23,340 --> 00:50:28,266
This isn't an ego trip.

449
00:50:28,286 --> 00:50:32,474
If you fill your whole vision with my face, right, where's yours?

450
00:50:32,534 --> 00:50:35,798
Where's your face?

451
00:50:39,324 --> 00:50:40,806
It's just there in your imagination, isn't it?

452
00:50:40,826 --> 00:50:41,887
You haven't a clue, have you?

453
00:50:43,318 --> 00:50:49,527
And when you look in the mirror and you look at your face, you think that's how people see you.

454
00:50:49,547 --> 00:50:50,128
At least I do.

455
00:50:51,030 --> 00:50:57,360
But it's only when you take another mirror and have a look at what's in the mirror that you realize that you didn't know your ears were that big.

456
00:50:59,844 --> 00:51:04,070
And you catch your face from the proper way that people see it.

457
00:51:04,510 --> 00:51:06,693
But normally that's not our vision of ourselves.

458
00:51:07,972 --> 00:51:17,527
So we walk around with this enormous delusion of either being ugly or beautiful, and it's completely our own idea of ourselves.

459
00:51:24,612 --> 00:51:33,065
So when you meditate or when you rather contemplate on these sorts of things, then again it's destroying this idea of who am I?

460
00:51:34,025 --> 00:51:34,606
Emotions.

461
00:51:34,726 --> 00:51:38,172
We know what control do we have over our emotions.

462
00:51:38,192 --> 00:51:41,157
You don't go to bed thinking, well, tomorrow I'll wake up depressed.

463
00:51:42,117 --> 00:51:43,119
You just wake up depressed.

464
00:51:43,519 --> 00:51:46,704
Tomorrow you say, I'll wake up happy, and you do, and you think, oh, I've got some control.

465
00:51:48,246 --> 00:51:49,650
But you haven't a clue how you're going to wake up.

466
00:51:50,030 --> 00:51:50,811
You might not wake up.

467
00:51:50,931 --> 00:51:51,311
Heavens.

468
00:51:53,418 --> 00:51:54,418
I mean, take that, you see.

469
00:51:54,699 --> 00:52:02,909
We go to sleep with a sheer presumption, a sheer presumption that tomorrow we're going to wake up.

470
00:52:02,989 --> 00:52:11,880
You go to bed, you feel absolutely comfortable, you're all curled up and it's all nice and warm, and there's just this underlying presumption that I'm going to wake up.

471
00:52:12,621 --> 00:52:18,610
Now, if the doctor said to you, you fall asleep, it looks like curtains to me.

472
00:52:18,630 --> 00:52:20,472
You'd be there with pins in your eyes and

473
00:52:23,101 --> 00:52:24,063
Pulling your nails out.

474
00:52:24,643 --> 00:52:26,186
Anything to keep awake.

475
00:52:28,309 --> 00:52:32,596
But we're quite happy to lose the self for 8, 10 hours.

476
00:52:32,856 --> 00:52:33,757
Some people 16.

477
00:52:34,398 --> 00:52:37,704
As long as we're absolutely certain within ourselves it will reappear.

478
00:52:40,809 --> 00:52:44,876
And there's a lovely poem here which comes from my favourite author.

479
00:52:45,197 --> 00:52:47,320
Some of you might know Samuel Beckett.

480
00:52:48,885 --> 00:52:53,231
He's known for his, you know, getting to grips with death.

481
00:52:53,331 --> 00:52:58,757
I mean, he's got one of his plays was just a mouth to speaking.

482
00:52:59,237 --> 00:53:01,219
And every so often it would wake up, still here.

483
00:53:01,481 --> 00:53:03,202
That was one of the sort of refrains.

484
00:53:03,282 --> 00:53:03,943
It would just stop.

485
00:53:05,465 --> 00:53:05,945
Still here.

486
00:53:07,467 --> 00:53:12,213
And he's at the edge of death as to what happens when you die.

487
00:53:14,014 --> 00:53:17,099
And he's got this very simple but sort of lovely poem.

488
00:53:17,119 --> 00:53:18,740
He says, just think

489
00:53:20,239 --> 00:53:32,331
If all this, one day, just one fine day, just think, if one fine day, all this stopped.

490
00:53:37,536 --> 00:53:39,759
I like that.

491
00:53:39,778 --> 00:53:47,226
So, going back now to the Buddha's original sort of understandings,

492
00:53:47,476 --> 00:53:49,298
So he's had this experience.

493
00:53:49,898 --> 00:53:55,047
He now comes back on himself and he spends his time reflecting on how he got there.

494
00:53:55,327 --> 00:53:59,893
And he comes up with this wheel of dependent origination, which is the psychology of suffering.

495
00:53:59,932 --> 00:54:00,655
That's all it's about.

496
00:54:00,675 --> 00:54:02,056
It's the psychology of delusion.

497
00:54:03,137 --> 00:54:07,164
And he sees these three vantage points and that's what he begins to teach.

498
00:54:07,563 --> 00:54:08,465
That's all he's teaching.

499
00:54:09,166 --> 00:54:17,398
To get into this position, the vipassana, to see things as they really are and to observe these three points of view.

500
00:54:19,048 --> 00:54:29,623
When we finally make it, when we have the glimpse at least of Nibbana, he also talks about it in this way.

501
00:54:35,851 --> 00:54:43,322
There is a sphere, so we go back to the idea of a sphere, where there is neither earth nor water, nor fire nor wind.

502
00:54:44,503 --> 00:54:44,583
Hmm?

503
00:54:45,070 --> 00:54:51,719
Now you've got to be careful here because this comes from a question as to where does the physical earth end?

504
00:54:53,121 --> 00:54:54,824
And he doesn't say the physical earth ends.

505
00:54:54,864 --> 00:54:59,251
He says there's a place where it finds no footing, which is very different.

506
00:54:59,711 --> 00:55:05,061
So the Buddha's enlightenment did not destroy his body.

507
00:55:06,523 --> 00:55:08,204
He just found a different relationship with it.

508
00:55:08,967 --> 00:55:11,230
And for the rest of his life, 40 odd years,

509
00:55:11,885 --> 00:55:13,927
he lived in what he called Nibbana.

510
00:55:14,307 --> 00:55:15,628
And that's Nibbana in this life.

511
00:55:17,530 --> 00:55:25,539
Where there's no infinite space, consciousness, nothingness, perception or non-perception, these refer to the four Rupajanas, Arupajanas.

512
00:55:26,340 --> 00:55:29,605
He says, no this world, no next world, no sun, no moon.

513
00:55:30,485 --> 00:55:36,152
There is, I say, no coming, no going, and no standing still.

514
00:55:37,054 --> 00:55:40,137
Now, we can understand in our meditation that

515
00:55:40,690 --> 00:55:47,335
the no coming and no going, because we can stand above in our meditation, things arising and passing away.

516
00:55:48,617 --> 00:55:51,119
But there's also no standing still.

517
00:55:51,400 --> 00:55:55,985
In other words, that's not a position in relation to what's happening.

518
00:55:57,887 --> 00:55:59,949
It's transcendent, completely transcendent.

519
00:56:01,750 --> 00:56:04,052
There's no passing away and there's no arising.

520
00:56:04,972 --> 00:56:06,494
It is without ground.

521
00:56:07,675 --> 00:56:08,757
It's without ground.

522
00:56:08,972 --> 00:56:10,097
There's nothing underneath it.

523
00:56:10,137 --> 00:56:11,079
There's nothing holding it.

524
00:56:12,143 --> 00:56:14,612
It's without foundation and it's without support.

525
00:56:15,474 --> 00:56:18,364
And he says, just this is the end of suffering.

526
00:56:18,385 --> 00:56:19,387
Just this is the end of it.

527
00:56:19,873 --> 00:56:41,005
Now, I'm going to suggest to you that in your meditation, when you get at least the position of very clearly being the observer, an observer of pain, an observer of physical pleasure, an observer of emotions, an observer of thought,

528
00:56:41,271 --> 00:56:53,724
Even though we can't say that's a pure nibbana because there's still the self there, at least we've got some idea there that there is no coming, no going, and there's no standing still within that process.

529
00:56:56,806 --> 00:57:06,556
And it's recognizing that that will draw your interest into really beginning to see that everything we experience is not me, not mine.

530
00:57:08,237 --> 00:57:08,797
And then...

531
00:57:09,992 --> 00:57:16,766
In those quiet moments, when you're very still, when there's just the breath, and you get that very strong sense of being the observer.

532
00:57:17,750 --> 00:57:21,838
So now that's the subtlest of things that we produce.

533
00:57:21,998 --> 00:57:29,655
That's the subtlest of things that the delusion has produced, this idea of I'm the observer.

534
00:57:29,635 --> 00:57:30,295
This is me.

535
00:57:31,197 --> 00:57:34,402
And that is a reflection in the mind.

536
00:57:35,103 --> 00:57:38,168
So the image I use is when we watch TV.

537
00:57:38,610 --> 00:57:41,614
When you watch TV sometimes, you can see your image in the screen.

538
00:57:42,976 --> 00:57:43,838
Now you've got a choice.

539
00:57:43,858 --> 00:57:46,722
You're going to watch yourself watching TV or you're going to watch TV.

540
00:57:47,724 --> 00:57:52,032
If you watch TV, you then lose that sense of self which is in the screen.

541
00:57:52,804 --> 00:58:07,007
And that's what happens when in your meditation you feel yourself to be the observer and you're looking with interest at an object such as a feeling or a sensation and suddenly there's that collapse into it.

542
00:58:08,289 --> 00:58:10,813
That collapse into it is the loss of self.

543
00:58:11,688 --> 00:58:21,822
And it's a direct perception by this satipanya, this Buddha within, this intelligent awareness of exactly what's going on.

544
00:58:22,364 --> 00:58:31,496
And when we come away from that sort of experience, whether we like it or not, or whether we're even aware of it or not, there's been some undermining of delusion.

545
00:58:32,778 --> 00:58:36,885
Those are the little power points.

546
00:58:37,657 --> 00:58:40,902
Often, when we're in that, there doesn't seem to be a comeback.

547
00:58:40,943 --> 00:58:43,286
We don't seem to have some sort of understanding.

548
00:58:44,108 --> 00:58:52,699
But in time, remember, there's this subtle change going on with the way we're looking at things.

549
00:58:53,380 --> 00:58:56,947
And it's changing the level of consciousness we're at.

550
00:58:57,427 --> 00:59:02,534
It's a very slow process, that's how it feels, of this slow changing, yeah.

551
00:59:02,920 --> 00:59:07,625
And every so often, there may an insight come in terms of words, a sudden understanding.

552
00:59:07,864 --> 00:59:10,588
You suddenly find yourself behaving in a different manner.

553
00:59:11,288 --> 00:59:14,431
You're reacting to a situation in a different way than you did before.

554
00:59:14,851 --> 00:59:16,152
And all these are telltales.

555
00:59:17,074 --> 00:59:20,097
So here, we enter into the Eightfold Path.

556
00:59:20,516 --> 00:59:28,846
So from right understanding, moving into right attitude, it expresses itself through right speech, right action, right livelihood.

557
00:59:29,746 --> 00:59:30,226
Now,

558
00:59:30,527 --> 00:59:38,199
This Noble Eightfold Path, remember, starts at any of those points.

559
00:59:38,679 --> 00:59:52,820
So when you make the effort to speak well, to speak truthfully and all that, when you make the effort to do something which is wholesome, when your livelihood has a wholesome effect on you, it reverberates back on your attitudes.

560
00:59:52,840 --> 00:59:54,722
It reverberates back on your understanding.

561
00:59:55,204 --> 00:59:57,226
So the whole thing turns upon itself.

562
00:59:58,088 --> 00:59:59,369
Turns upon itself.

563
00:59:59,789 --> 01:00:09,324
And in this way, over a period of time, we do feel a certain change within ourselves, hopefully for the better.

564
01:00:13,690 --> 01:00:17,155
So I think that brings me to a sore throat.

565
01:00:22,322 --> 01:00:24,126
So I think I'd better stop before I die.

566
01:00:25,016 --> 01:00:33,172
So I hope my words have been of some assistance and I can only hope that in the very shortest length of time you will be fully liberated.

567
01:00:37,860 --> 01:00:38,402
Thank you.

